\section{Methodology}

In this section, we present MACVO-Net (Multi-scale Angular Cost Volume Network), a unified architecture tailored for non-Lambertian light field depth estimation. Unlike conventional EPI-based networks that rely on rigid 2D slices and discard over 65\% of angular information, our architecture executes a paradigm shift towards an explicit 4D cost volume formulation \cite{heber2018}. By comprehensively utilizing all available angular views, MACVO-Net constructs a holistic geometric consistency metric that naturally integrates the physical modeling of non-Lambertian reflectance. Fig.~\ref{fig:architecture} illustrates the network topology, which bridges explicit photometric warping with multi-scale feature refinement to decode complex surface properties.

The network ingests a standard 4D light field as input, comprising $N_v = 81$ angular views arranged in a $9 \times 9$ grid, denoted as $I \in \mathbb{R}^{81 \times H \times W \times 3}$. During preprocessing, the raw light field captured by the plenoptic array is parsed into a structured tensor, from which the central perspective, $I_{center}$, is extracted. The spatial dimensions, $H \times W$, are standardized to $128 \times 128$ to balance computational efficiency and structural fidelity. This complete $9 \times 9$ angular arrangement preserves the comprehensive spatial-angular sampling required for robust view warping operations and the implicit extraction of non-Lambertian physical characteristics, operating independently of sparse directional constraints \cite{ng2005}.

The data flow follows a dual-branch architecture designed to extract both spatial semantics and explicit multi-view geometry. As depicted in Fig.~\ref{fig:architecture}, the FeatureEncoder first processes the central view, $I_{center}$, to generate multi-scale representations. It yields hierarchical feature maps $F_i = f_{enc_i}(F_{i-1})$ with $F_0 = I_{center}$, progressively expanding channel capacities from 32 to 128 to capture spatial context. Concurrently, the CostVolumeBuilder leverages the entire $81$-view array to construct a $4D$ cost volume. For $N_d = 32$ discrete disparity hypotheses, it warps the $80$ non-central views to the central reference frame and aggregates photometric errors:
\begin{equation}
    CV(d, p) = \sum_{v=1}^{80} \| W(I_v, d, p) - I_{center}(p) \|,
\end{equation}
where $W$ denotes the spatial warping operation governed by the disparity hypothesis $d$, and $p$ indicates spatial pixel coordinates. The resulting cost volume, $CV \in \mathbb{R}^{32 \times H \times W}$, is concatenated with the initial $32$-channel center-view features and fed into the U-Net Encoder. This encoder extracts high-dimensional features across three downsampling stages, increasing channels from $64 \rightarrow 128 \rightarrow 256$, while supplying intermediate activations to the decoder via skip connections \cite{ronneberger2015}.

The U-Net Decoder manages the final depth inference by progressively upsampling the deep feature tensors to their original spatial resolution. At each scale, it fuses the high-level semantic features from the decoder with the low-level geometric boundaries relayed through skip connections. Governed by $D_i = f_{up_i}([D_{i-1}, E_i])$, this multi-scale refinement mechanism allows the network to identify inherently flat cost volumes generated by non-Lambertian surfaces and interpret them as explicit uncertainty signals, thereby propagating accurate depth from neighboring valid pixels \cite{blinn1977}. The final layer applies a convolution followed by a sigmoid activation function, yielding a single-channel output tensor of shape $(B, 1, H, W)$. During post-processing, this dense disparity map is linearly scaled by the predefined maximum disparity threshold to reconstruct the absolute depth map of the scene.

\subsection{FeatureEncoder (特征编码器)}

