The FeatureEncoder module decouples spatial feature extraction from the angular domain to establish a robust geometric and contextual anchor for the MACVO-Net architecture. In non-Lambertian scenarios, high-frequency specular highlights and reflections corrupt photometric consistency across angular views, frequently yielding ambiguous cost volumes. By isolating the feature encoding of the central view, this module preserves high-fidelity structural boundaries and aggregates hierarchical semantic context. Unlike conventional EPI-based frameworks that entangle spatial and angular feature extraction within a single convolutional stream \cite{heber2018}, this explicit decoupling allows the network to independently optimize spatial regularization and geometric matching, thereby preventing non-Lambertian artifacts from degrading the initial feature representations.

The module ingests the extracted central view, denoted as $I_{center} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C \times H \times W}$, where $B$ represents the batch size, $C=3$ corresponds to the RGB channels, and $H$ and $W$ define the spatial dimensions (e.g., $128 \times 128$). A hierarchical three-stage convolutional pipeline processes the input, applying spatial downsampling while proportionally expanding the channel capacity to compress and retain critical spatial details. The transformation at each encoding stage is formalized as follows:
