\section{Experiments}

To rigorously evaluate the proposed unified dual-mask physical model for non-Lambertian light field depth estimation, we assemble a comprehensive suite of benchmark datasets. This suite spans from standard spatially complex scenes to extreme non-Lambertian environments dominated by severe specular and translucent materials. The strategic selection of these datasets is explicitly designed to highlight the structural limitations of traditional 2D Epipolar Plane Image (EPI) slicing paradigms and to validate the superiority of our full-angular 4D cost volume framework in decoding complex global light transport phenomena.

\textbf{HCI 4D Light Field Datasets (HCInew and HCI-Old).} 
We utilize both the modern (HCInew) and legacy (HCI-Old) Heidelberg Collaborative Imaging datasets, which serve as the standard benchmarks for 4D light field research. The HCInew dataset provides four meticulously crafted high-resolution complex indoor/outdoor scenes (\textit{e.g.}, Boxes, Cotton, Dino, Sideboard). These scenes feature a mixture of standard Lambertian surfaces and mild non-Lambertian properties, such as soft specularities and subtle translucency. Each scene comprises a $9 \times 9$ angular resolution with a spatial resolution of $512 \times 512$ pixels. Highly accurate ground-truth depth maps are generated using laser scanning. The legacy HCI-Old dataset provides four additional scenes with different optical configurations. We exclusively use the scenes from HCInew and HCI-Old for \textit{testing} our model's generalization capability on moderately complex real-world materials, ensuring no training data overlaps with these standard evaluation scenes.

\textbf{Wanner Dataset.} 
To evaluate the robustness of our dual-mask physical model against strong specular reflections and complex geometry, we incorporate the Wanner light field dataset. This dataset contains highly challenging scenes captured with a dense $9 \times 9$ angular resolution, specifically featuring non-Lambertian surfaces with severe mirror-like reflections and transparent objects. The ground-truth depth maps are obtained via a robust optical flow-based alignment technique. Following the evaluation protocols established in prior arts, we adopt this dataset solely for testing to benchmark our method's accuracy under strong directional light transport violations.

\textbf{Non-Lambertian Dataset (Zhenglong).} 
To specifically target the catastrophic failure modes of EPI-based paradigms, we extensively train and validate our network on the Non-Lambertian dataset. This dataset is explicitly constructed to feature extreme global light transport effects, including heavy refractions through thick glass, multi-path reflections off metallic surfaces, and highly translucent materials. The angular views are captured using a Lytro Illum plenoptic camera and raw light field files are decoded into sub-aperture images. The dataset is divided into multiple complex scenarios. We partition this dataset into a training set, a validation set, and a dedicated testing set, ensuring that similar material types (\textit{e.g.}, purely transparent glass vs. tinted glass) are distributed across all splits to prevent data leakage. 

\textbf{Data Preprocessing and Feature Formulation.} 
Due to the massive memory footprint of 4D light fields, raw sub-aperture images cannot be directly fed into the full-angular 4D cost volume. Instead, we apply an offline preprocessing pipeline to extract compact pixel-level feature representations. For each dataset, we compute the MRI-inspired angular frequency analysis and SAM-guided energy adjustments, generating dense feature maps. These pre-computed pixel feature maps (stored in the respective \textit{pixel\_feature\_maps} directories) encode the essential physical multi-view evidence required to decouple specular reflections, reducing the dimensionality of the input while preserving the critical non-Lambertian physical cues.

