The proposed Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model is implemented using PyTorch. All experiments are conducted on a workstation equipped with a single NVIDIA RTX 4090 GPU (24GB VRAM) and an Intel Core i9-13900K CPU. 

During the training phase, we utilize the AdamW optimizer with an initial learning rate of $1 \times 10^{-4}$ and a weight decay of $1 \times 10^{-4}$. A cosine annealing scheduler is adopted to gradually decay the learning rate to a minimum of $1 \times 10^{-6}$. The model is trained for 100 epochs with an effective batch size of 8. Due to the high memory footprint of 4D light field data, we set the physical batch size to 4 and enable a gradient accumulation step of 2. Training the network to full convergence takes approximately 18 hours. 

To enhance the generalization capability of the model and mitigate overfitting, we employ a comprehensive set of online data augmentation strategies. The input light field sub-aperture images (SAIs) are randomly cropped to a spatial resolution of $256 \times 256$ pixels. Additionally, standard augmentations—including random horizontal and vertical flipping, random $90^{\circ}$ rotations, and photometric distortions (brightness and gamma jittering)—are applied to the spatial domain.

The overall objective function is formulated as a weighted combination of a depth regression loss $\mathcal{L}_{depth}$, a physical dual-mask consistency loss $\mathcal{L}_{mask}$, and an edge-aware smoothness regularization term $\mathcal{L}_{smooth}$. Based on empirical validation on the training set, the balancing weights for these components are set to $\lambda_{depth} = 1.0$, $\lambda_{mask} = 0.5$, and $\lambda_{smooth} = 0.1$, respectively. 

To rigorously evaluate the performance of the proposed method against state-of-the-art approaches, we adopt three standard metrics widely used in light field depth estimation: Mean Squared Error (MSE), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), and Bad Pixel Ratio (BadPix). Given a ground truth depth map $d$ and the estimated depth map $\hat{d}$, each containing $N$ valid pixels, the metrics are defined as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{MSE (Mean Squared Error):} Measures the average of the squared discrepancies between the estimated and ground truth depths.
    \begin{equation}
        \text{MSE} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} (\hat{d}_i - d_i)^2
    \end{equation}

    \item \textbf{MAE (Mean Absolute Error):} Represents the average absolute deviation between the estimated and ground truth depths, providing an intuitive measure of the prediction accuracy.
    \begin{equation}
        \text{MAE} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} |\hat{d}_i - d_i|
    \end{equation}

    \item \textbf{BadPix:} Evaluates the spatial robustness of the algorithm by computing the percentage of pixels where the absolute disparity error exceeds a predefined threshold $\tau$. Following standard light field benchmarks, we set the threshold $\tau = 0.07$.
    \begin{equation}
        \text{BadPix} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \mathbb{I}\left( |\hat{d}_i - d_i| > \tau \right) \times 100\%
    \end{equation}
    where $\mathbb{I}(\cdot)$ is the indicator function, which returns $1$ if the condition is true and $0$ otherwise.
\end{itemize}

