Table~\ref{tab:sota_comparison} details the quantitative results using Mean Square Error (MSE), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), and Bad Pixel rate (BadPix). As illustrated, our unified architecture achieves highly competitive performance across all evaluated datasets. The most substantial improvements are observed in the Stanford Non-Lambertian and Heidelberg Mixed datasets. For instance, on the Stanford dataset, MACVO-Net significantly reduces the MAE to 0.042 and lowers the MSE to 2.10, outperforming previous robust methods by a large margin. This advantage stems directly from our explicit 4D cost volume formulation, which comprehensively utilizes all available angular views. Unlike conventional EPI slices that discard over 65\% of angular information and fail under complex reflectance, our holistic geometric metric naturally integrates the physical modeling of non-Lambertian reflectance.

Furthermore, the global geometric consistency descriptor (GCD) and the SAM-guided ternary mask play pivotal roles in handling mixed reflectance scenarios. By dynamically adjusting the alpha parameter according to regional roughness, our model effectively suppresses the high-frequency noise introduced by specular reflections without over-smoothing diffuse regions. This adaptive mechanism ensures robust depth estimation in highly textured mixed scenes, as evidenced by the 24.5\% reduction in BadPix on the Heidelberg Mixed dataset compared to the strong baseline \cite{wang2023}.

Although our unified framework generally excels, it slightly trails the specialized method by Zhang \textit{et al.} \cite{zhang2023} in the BadPix metric on the Stanford dataset. This specific performance gap arises because their algorithm utilizes highly specialized, hand-crafted priors explicitly engineered for transparent object boundaries. In contrast, our SAM-guided mask aggressively suppresses specular noise to ensure overall stability across the unified dual-mask space. Consequently, this strategy occasionally over-smooths ultra-sharp transparent edges to maintain global physical consistency, marginally increasing the BadPix rate at exact object boundaries. Despite this slight trade-off, our model successfully maintains the lowest MAE and MSE on the Stanford dataset, demonstrating its superior overall geometric reconstruction capability.

