\textbf{Impact of Component-aware Fusion.} Removing the component-aware fusion mechanism and uniformly applying the EPI-based depth estimation across all regions leads to the most severe performance degradation. Specifically, the MAE increases drastically from 0.131 to 0.285, a relative drop of 117.5\%. This deterioration occurs because traditional epipolar plane image (EPI) methods strictly assume Lambertian reflections \cite{heber2018}. Without our tailored fusion strategy, formulated as $D = w_d D_{\text{EPI}} + w_s D_{\text{specular}} + w_{sc} D_{\text{scatter}}$, the network fails to resolve the severe correspondence ambiguities introduced by non-Lambertian scattering and specular highlights.

\textbf{Impact of MRI-based Angular Frequency Analysis.} Replacing our MRI-inspired 2D Discrete Fourier Transform with a standard convolutional layer for angular feature extraction causes the MAE to rise by 48.8\% to 0.195. This observation empirically validates our physical insight that explicitly decoupling the angular spectrum effectively differentiates distinct reflection types. By mapping the $9\times 9$ angular samples into the frequency domain, our approach explicitly isolates the high-frequency peaks characteristic of specular reflections from the low-frequency dominance of diffuse surfaces \cite{levin2011}.

\textbf{Impact of Dual-Mask Physical Modeling.} The dual-mask formulation constitutes the core of our physical interpretability. When ablating the medium mask $M_{\text{med}}(x,y)$, which quantifies pixel-level roughness, the network can no longer accurately parameterize the Bidirectional Reflectance Distribution Function weights. Consequently, the MAE surges to 0.218. This substantial margin confirms that distinguishing between specular regions ($r \ll 1$) and diffuse regions ($r \gg 1$) is indispensable for robust depth retrieval, tightly aligning with classical light reflection models \cite{blinn1977}. Furthermore, discarding the angular direction mask $M_{\text{ang}}(x,y)$ degrades the MAE to 0.175. Without the deflection vector field $\Delta\bm{k}(x,y)$, the proposed framework loses its capacity to track wave vector shifts, thereby failing to correct the distorted light paths caused by complex non-Lambertian materials. These empirical findings ultimately underscore the fundamental necessity of transcending the structural limitations of traditional light field paradigms.
